1
00:00:43,500 --> 00:00:47,159
 And I'd like to welcome you to this videotape course on

2
00:00:47,159 --> 00:00:47,899
 signals and systems.

3
00:00:50,109 --> 00:00:54,030
 Signals, at least as an informal definition, are

4
00:00:54,689 --> 00:00:58,450
 functions of one or more independent variables that

5
00:00:58,450 --> 00:01:00,929
 typically carry some type of information.

6
00:01:02,229 --> 00:01:06,650
 Systems, in our setting, would typically be used to process

7
00:01:06,650 --> 00:01:07,129
 signals.

8
00:01:08,609 --> 00:01:12,650
 One very common example of a signal might be, let's say, a

9
00:01:12,650 --> 00:01:13,390
 a speech signal.

10
00:01:13,650 --> 00:01:17,549
 And you might think of the air pressure as a function of

11
00:01:17,549 --> 00:01:20,829
 time, or perhaps the electrical signal after it

12
00:01:20,829 --> 00:01:23,469
 goes through the microphone transducer as a function of

13
00:01:23,469 --> 00:01:26,370
 time, as representing the speech signal.

14
00:01:26,670 --> 00:01:30,930
 And we might see a typical speech signal looking

15
00:01:30,930 --> 00:01:32,930
 something like I've indicated here.

16
00:01:33,810 --> 00:01:37,549
 It's a function of time in this particular case.

17
00:01:37,549 --> 00:01:42,090
 case, and the independent variable, being time, is in

18
00:01:42,090 --> 00:01:43,329
 fact continuous.

19
00:01:44,030 --> 00:01:47,430
 And so a signal like this we will typically be referring to

20
00:01:47,430 --> 00:01:49,609
 as a continuous time signal.

21
00:01:51,269 --> 00:01:55,129
 Now it also, for this particular example, is a

22
00:01:55,129 --> 00:02:00,430
 function of one independent variable, and that will be

23
00:02:00,430 --> 00:02:05,890
 referred to as a one-dimensional signal

24
00:02:05,890 --> 00:02:10,110
 corresponding to the fact that there's only one independent

25
00:02:10,110 --> 00:02:12,750
 variable instead of several independent variables.

26
00:02:13,669 --> 00:02:18,729
 So a speech signal is an example of a continuous time

27
00:02:19,050 --> 00:02:20,330
 one-dimensional signal.

28
00:02:21,250 --> 00:02:26,229
 Now, signals can, of course, be multidimensional, and they

29
00:02:26,229 --> 00:02:27,830
 may not have as their independent

30
00:02:27,830 --> 00:02:29,389
 variables time variables.

31
00:02:29,629 --> 00:02:33,770
 One very common example are the examples

32
00:02:33,770 --> 00:02:34,930
 represented by images.

33
00:02:35,550 --> 00:02:41,090
 Images, as signals, we might think of as representing

34
00:02:41,090 --> 00:02:46,069
 brightness, as it varies in a horizontal and

35
00:02:46,069 --> 00:02:47,650
 vertical direction.

36
00:02:48,090 --> 00:02:51,469
 And so the brightness, as a function of these two spatial

37
00:02:51,469 --> 00:02:55,969
 variables, is then a two-dimensional signal.

38
00:03:02,330 --> 00:03:06,490
 The independent variables would typically be continuous,

39
00:03:06,490 --> 00:03:09,270
 continuous, but of course they're not time variables.

40
00:03:09,669 --> 00:03:14,509
 And incidentally, it's worth just commenting that very

41
00:03:14,509 --> 00:03:18,629
 often, simply for convenience, we'll have a tendency to refer

42
00:03:18,629 --> 00:03:22,090
 to the independent variables when we talk about signals as

43
00:03:22,090 --> 00:03:25,389
 time variables, whether or not they really do represent time.

44
00:03:27,009 --> 00:03:31,090
 Well, let me illustrate one example of an image.

45
00:03:31,090 --> 00:03:46,750
 And this is a picture of JBJ Fourier, who perhaps more than anyone else, is responsible for the elegance and beauty of a lot of the concepts that we'll be talking about throughout this course.

46
00:03:46,750 --> 00:03:55,610
 And when you look at this, in addition to seeing Fourier himself, you should recognize that what you're looking at is basically a signal,

47
00:03:55,770 --> 00:04:01,490
 which is brightness as a function of the horizontal and vertical spatial variables.

48
00:04:02,689 --> 00:04:09,530
 As another example of an image as a signal, let's look at an aerial photograph.

49
00:04:09,530 --> 00:04:17,129
 photograph. This is an aerial photograph taken over a set of roads, which you can more or less

50
00:04:17,129 --> 00:04:22,930
 recognize in the picture. And one of the difficulties with this signal is that the

51
00:04:22,930 --> 00:04:31,170
 road system is somewhat obscured by cloud cover. And what I'll want to show later as an example

52
00:04:31,170 --> 00:04:38,470
 of what a system might do to such a signal in terms of processing it is an attempt to at least

53
00:04:38,470 --> 00:04:43,050
 compensate somewhat for the cloud cover that's represented

54
00:04:43,050 --> 00:04:43,850
 in the photograph.

55
00:04:44,329 --> 00:04:47,990
 Although in terms of the detailed analysis that we go

56
00:04:47,990 --> 00:04:52,449
 through during the course, our focus of attention is pretty

57
00:04:52,449 --> 00:04:54,490
 much restricted to one-dimensional signals.

58
00:04:54,709 --> 00:04:58,730
 In fact, we will be using two-dimensional signals, more

59
00:04:58,730 --> 00:05:02,509
 specifically images, very often to illustrate a variety

60
00:05:02,769 --> 00:05:03,829
 of concepts.

61
00:05:03,829 --> 00:05:03,970
 sets.

62
00:05:05,709 --> 00:05:10,629
 Now, speech and images are examples of what we've referred

63
00:05:10,629 --> 00:05:16,189
 to as continuous time signals in that they are functions of

64
00:05:16,189 --> 00:05:17,529
 continuous variables.

65
00:05:18,589 --> 00:05:22,310
 An equally important class of signals that we will be

66
00:05:22,310 --> 00:05:27,389
 concentrating on in the course are signals that are discrete

67
00:05:27,389 --> 00:05:33,449
 discrete time signals, where by discrete time, what we mean

68
00:05:33,449 --> 00:05:38,550
 is that the signal is a function of an integer

69
00:05:38,550 --> 00:05:43,990
 variable, and so specifically only takes on values at

70
00:05:44,300 --> 00:05:46,889
 integer values of the argument.

71
00:05:47,819 --> 00:05:53,009
 So here is a graphical illustration of a discrete

72
00:05:53,009 --> 00:05:53,790
 time signal.

73
00:05:53,790 --> 00:05:58,029
 and discrete time signals arise in a variety of ways.

74
00:05:58,189 --> 00:06:04,949
 One very common example that is seen fairly often is discrete time signals

75
00:06:04,949 --> 00:06:12,069
 in the context of economic time series and, for example, stock market analysis.

76
00:06:12,569 --> 00:06:20,230
 So what I show here is one very commonly occurring example of a discrete time signal.

77
00:06:20,230 --> 00:06:24,550
 It represents the weekly stock market index.

78
00:06:24,810 --> 00:06:29,410
 The independent variable in this case is the week number,

79
00:06:29,689 --> 00:06:35,470
 and we see what the stock market is doing over this particular period

80
00:06:35,470 --> 00:06:39,709
 as a function of the number of the week and, of course,

81
00:06:39,750 --> 00:06:43,670
 along the vertical axis is the weekly index.

82
00:06:44,410 --> 00:06:49,910
 Incidentally, this particular period was not chosen at random.

83
00:06:49,910 --> 00:06:57,490
 It, in fact, captures a very interesting aspect of stock market history, namely the stock

84
00:06:57,490 --> 00:07:06,170
 market crash in 1929, which, in fact, is represented by the behavior of this discrete time signal

85
00:07:06,170 --> 00:07:09,610
 or sequence in this particular area.

86
00:07:09,769 --> 00:07:14,810
 So this dramatic dip, in fact, is the stock market crash of 1929.

87
00:07:15,870 --> 00:07:21,089
 Well, the Dow Jones weekly average is an example of a

88
00:07:21,089 --> 00:07:23,410
 one-dimensional discrete time signal.

89
00:07:24,370 --> 00:07:29,009
 And just as with continuous time, we had not just

90
00:07:29,009 --> 00:07:30,850
 one-dimensional, but multi-dimensional signals,

91
00:07:31,350 --> 00:07:35,230
 likewise, we have multi-dimensional signals in

92
00:07:35,689 --> 00:07:41,110
 the discrete time case, where in that case, then, the

93
00:07:41,110 --> 00:07:43,850
 The discrete time signal that we're talking about, or

94
00:07:43,850 --> 00:07:47,370
 sequence, is a function of two integer variables.

95
00:07:47,810 --> 00:07:51,990
 And as one example, this might, let's say, represent a

96
00:07:51,990 --> 00:07:58,230
 spatial antenna array, where this is array number in, let's

97
00:07:58,230 --> 00:08:01,670
 say, the horizontal direction, and this is array number in

98
00:08:01,670 --> 00:08:02,410
 the vertical direction.

99
00:08:03,110 --> 00:08:06,230
 Both classes of signals, continuous time and discrete

100
00:08:06,230 --> 00:08:09,149
 time, as I've indicated, are very important.

101
00:08:09,149 --> 00:08:15,569
 important, and it should be emphasized that the importance of discrete time signals and

102
00:08:15,569 --> 00:08:22,730
 associated processing continues to grow in large part because of the current and emerging

103
00:08:22,730 --> 00:08:32,669
 technologies that permit basically the processing of continuous time signals by first converting

104
00:08:32,669 --> 00:08:37,230
 them to discrete time signals and processing them with discrete time systems.

105
00:08:37,230 --> 00:08:42,309
 And that, in fact, is a topic that we will discuss in a fair

106
00:08:42,309 --> 00:08:44,610
 amount of detail later on in the course.

107
00:08:47,159 --> 00:08:50,720
 Let's now turn our attention to systems.

108
00:08:51,440 --> 00:08:57,080
 And as I indicated, a system basically processes signals.

109
00:08:58,039 --> 00:09:01,899
 And they have, of course, inputs and outputs.

110
00:09:02,360 --> 00:09:06,279
 And depending on whether we're talking about continuous time

111
00:09:06,279 --> 00:09:11,120
 time or discrete time, the system may be a continuous time

112
00:09:11,120 --> 00:09:13,779
 system or a discrete time system.

113
00:09:14,100 --> 00:09:17,620
 So in the continuous time case, I indicate here an

114
00:09:17,620 --> 00:09:20,620
 input x of t and an output y of t.

115
00:09:20,919 --> 00:09:24,899
 If we were talking about a discrete time system, I would

116
00:09:24,899 --> 00:09:29,740
 represent the input in terms of a discrete time variable

117
00:09:30,080 --> 00:09:32,820
 and, of course, the output in terms of a

118
00:09:32,820 --> 00:09:34,200
 discrete time variable also.

119
00:09:34,200 --> 00:09:40,440
 So now, in very general terms, systems are hard to deal with

120
00:09:40,440 --> 00:09:44,720
 because they are defined very broadly and very generally.

121
00:09:45,120 --> 00:09:49,679
 And in dealing with systems and analyzing them, what we

122
00:09:49,679 --> 00:09:55,000
 will do is attempt to exploit some very specific and, as

123
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:57,799
 we'll see, very useful system properties.

124
00:09:57,799 --> 00:09:57,940
 properties.

125
00:09:58,860 --> 00:10:05,659
 To indicate what I mean and how things might be split up, we could talk about systems,

126
00:10:05,840 --> 00:10:13,120
 and we'll talk about systems that are linear, and we could divide systems basically into

127
00:10:13,120 --> 00:10:22,360
 systems that are either linear or nonlinear, and we will, and also divide systems into

128
00:10:22,360 --> 00:10:26,100
 into systems that are what we'll refer to as time

129
00:10:26,100 --> 00:10:28,500
 invariant or time varying systems.

130
00:10:29,159 --> 00:10:33,080
 And these aren't terms that we've defined yet, of course,

131
00:10:33,179 --> 00:10:36,320
 but we will be defining in the course very shortly.

132
00:10:36,960 --> 00:10:40,500
 And while in some sense this division represents all

133
00:10:40,500 --> 00:10:45,440
 systems and this does too, the focus of the course is really

134
00:10:45,820 --> 00:10:50,000
 going to be principally on linear time invariant systems.

135
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:50,259
 systems.

136
00:10:50,460 --> 00:10:56,320
 So it's basically these systems that we will be focusing on.

137
00:10:56,960 --> 00:11:01,480
 And we'll be referring to those systems as linear time

138
00:11:01,480 --> 00:11:02,320
 invariant systems.

139
00:11:04,570 --> 00:11:07,929
 Well, as a brief glimpse at some of the kinds of things

140
00:11:07,929 --> 00:11:13,269
 that systems can do, let me illustrate first in a

141
00:11:13,889 --> 00:11:18,389
 one-dimensional continuous time context, and then later

142
00:11:18,389 --> 00:11:27,009
 with a discrete time example one example of some processing of signals with an

143
00:11:27,009 --> 00:11:30,470
 appropriate system the particular example that I want to illustrate

144
00:11:31,149 --> 00:11:37,049
 relates to the restoration of old recordings and this is some work that

145
00:11:37,049 --> 00:11:42,549
 was done by Professor Thomas Stockham who is at the University of Utah and

146
00:11:42,549 --> 00:11:48,190
 work that he had done a number of years ago relating to the fact that in old

147
00:11:48,190 --> 00:11:54,490
 recordings, for example in Caruso recordings, the recording was done

148
00:11:54,490 --> 00:11:59,889
 through a mechanical horn and the characteristics of the horn tended to

149
00:11:59,889 --> 00:12:04,889
 vary from day to day. And because of the characteristics of the horn, the

150
00:12:04,889 --> 00:12:10,070
 recording tended to have a muffled quality, something like this, sort of the

151
00:12:10,070 --> 00:12:15,169
 sense that you would get if you were speaking through a megaphone. What

152
00:12:15,169 --> 00:12:19,870
 What Professor Stockham did was develop a system to process

153
00:12:20,049 --> 00:12:25,309
 these old recordings in such a way that a lot of the

154
00:12:25,950 --> 00:12:29,210
 characteristics and distortion due to that recording system

155
00:12:29,210 --> 00:12:29,870
 was removed.

156
00:12:30,549 --> 00:12:34,730
 So I'd like to illustrate that as one example of some signal

157
00:12:34,730 --> 00:12:37,870
 processing with an appropriate continuous time system.

158
00:12:38,450 --> 00:12:42,210
 And what you'll hear is a two-track recording.

159
00:12:42,210 --> 00:12:47,009
 recording. On the first track is the original unrestored

160
00:12:47,009 --> 00:12:48,070
 Caruso recording.

161
00:12:48,509 --> 00:12:52,429
 And on the second track is the result of the restoration.

162
00:12:52,970 --> 00:12:56,789
 And so as I switch back and forth from channel one to

163
00:12:56,789 --> 00:13:00,769
 channel two, we'll be switching from the original to

164
00:13:00,769 --> 00:13:01,210
 the restored.

165
00:13:02,029 --> 00:13:05,529
 We'll begin the tape by playing the original.

166
00:13:05,809 --> 00:13:08,850
 And then as it proceeds, we'll switch.

167
00:13:08,850 --> 00:13:22,720
 switch. So we begin on channel one. That's the original recording. And switch now to

168
00:13:22,720 --> 00:13:47,610
 the processed. Now let's switch back. Back to the original. Back to the restoration.

169
00:13:54,620 --> 00:14:07,419
 and once again back to the original and presumably and hopefully what you heard

170
00:14:07,419 --> 00:14:13,059
 was that in the restoration in fact a lot of the muffled characteristics of

171
00:14:13,059 --> 00:14:20,220
 the original recording were compensated for or removed now one of the

172
00:14:20,220 --> 00:14:25,100
 interesting things that happened in fact in the work that professor Stockham did

173
00:14:25,100 --> 00:14:29,299
 is that in the process of the restoration and perhaps you heard this

174
00:14:29,299 --> 00:14:34,759
 In the process of the restoration, in fact, some of the background noise on the recording

175
00:14:35,340 --> 00:14:36,620
 was emphasized.

176
00:14:37,159 --> 00:14:44,600
 And so he processed the signal further in an attempt to remove that background noise.

177
00:14:44,919 --> 00:14:49,320
 And with that particular processing, the processing was very highly nonlinear.

178
00:14:50,679 --> 00:14:57,580
 A very interesting thing happened, which was that not only in that processing was the background

179
00:14:57,580 --> 00:15:04,000
 noise removed but somewhat surprisingly also the orchestra was removed and let

180
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:10,059
 me just play that now as an example of some very sophisticated processing with

181
00:15:10,059 --> 00:15:17,620
 a nonlinear system what you'll hear on channel one is the restoration as we had

182
00:15:17,620 --> 00:15:23,519
 just played it when I switched to channel two it will be after the

183
00:15:23,519 --> 00:15:26,539
 the processing with an attempt to remove the orchestra

184
00:15:26,539 --> 00:15:28,539
 and the background noise.

185
00:15:29,899 --> 00:15:30,799
 Channel one now.

186
00:15:38,200 --> 00:15:41,279
 And now with the noise and orchestra removed.

187
00:15:44,580 --> 00:15:45,700
 Back to channel one.

188
00:15:48,820 --> 00:16:02,159
 And finally, once again, with the orchestra removed.

189
00:16:11,269 --> 00:16:11,909
 OK.

190
00:16:12,110 --> 00:16:16,230
 So that's an example of processing of a continuous

191
00:16:16,230 --> 00:16:19,029
 time signal with a corresponding

192
00:16:19,029 --> 00:16:20,190
 continuous time system.

193
00:16:20,929 --> 00:16:25,669
 Now I'd like to illustrate an example of some processing on

194
00:16:25,669 --> 00:16:26,789
 a discrete time signal.

195
00:16:27,110 --> 00:16:30,690
 And I'd like to do that in the context of the example that I

196
00:16:30,690 --> 00:16:34,169
 showed before of a discrete time signal, which was the

197
00:16:34,169 --> 00:16:37,629
 the Dow Jones Industrial Weekly Stock Market Index.

198
00:16:38,389 --> 00:16:43,350
 I had shown it before, as I've shown it here again,

199
00:16:44,230 --> 00:16:46,990
 over a period of slightly more than a year,

200
00:16:47,129 --> 00:16:49,909
 where this is the number of weeks

201
00:16:49,909 --> 00:16:52,669
 and this is the weekly index.

202
00:16:53,450 --> 00:16:58,750
 And to illustrate some of the processing, what I'd like to do

203
00:16:58,750 --> 00:17:02,629
 is show the stock market index, the weekly index,

204
00:17:02,629 --> 00:17:04,609
 over a much longer time period.

205
00:17:04,849 --> 00:17:09,269
 In particular, the weekly index over a 10-year period.

206
00:17:09,710 --> 00:17:11,910
 And that's what I show here.

207
00:17:12,250 --> 00:17:18,250
 So what this covers is roughly 1927 to 1937.

208
00:17:18,750 --> 00:17:22,750
 And in this case, although this is still a discrete time

209
00:17:22,750 --> 00:17:26,210
 signal, just simply for the purposes of display, what

